      "role": "user",
      "content": "it passed the test which is good, but i'm worried it's a bit too reliant on those specific words. i just tried running it on this other paragraph from a different regulation and it completely missed a few things that are clearly requirements.\n\ntry this one:\n\n\"Users are obligated to provide a valid email address. It is necessary that the login credentials be encrypted. System administrators shall perform weekly audits.\"\n\nThe current regex didn't catch \"obligated\" or \"necessary\" or \"shall\". Can you update the function so it's more robust and actually passes this new set too?\n\n```python\ndef test_parser_v2():\n    sample_text_2 = (\n        \"Users are obligated to provide a valid email address. \"\n        \"It is necessary that the login credentials be encrypted. \"\n        \"System administrators shall perform weekly audits.\"\n    )\n    \n    expected_2 = [\n        \"provide a valid email address\",\n        \"the login credentials be encrypted\",\n        \"perform weekly audits\"\n    ]\n    \n    results = extract_requirements(sample_text_2)\n    \n    for req in expected_2:\n        assert any(req in r for r in results), f\"Failed to find: {req}\"\n    \n    print(\"V2 tests passed!\")\n\ntest_parser_v2()\n```",
